A picture is included below.

First, we determine the points of intersection. Setting the two curves
equal to each other, we have

\begin{align*}4-x^{2} = (x-2)^{2} = x^{2}-4x + 4\end{align*}

Bringing the terms to the right hand side, we have

\begin{align*}0 = 2x^{2}-4x = 2x(x-2)\end{align*}

and so the points of intersection are $x = 0$ and $x=2$. Notice either
form the picture or testing a point between 0 and 2 (say $x=1$) and
plugging it into both equations, we see that the curve $4-x^{2}$ is
bigger between 0 and 2. Hence, our area is

\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{2} (4-x^{2} - (x-2)^{2})\, dx &= \int_{0}^{2} (4-x^{2} - x^{2} + 4x - 4)\, dx \\
&= \int_{0}^{2} (-2x^{2} + 4x)\, dx \\
&= \left. \frac{-2x^{3}}{3} + 2x^{2}\right|_{0}^{2} \\
&= \frac{-2(2)^{3}}{3} + 2(2)^{2}\\
&= \frac{8}{3}\end{align*}

completing the question.

